							Gary Gerhardt recently reported in the <i>Rocky Mountain News</i> (<a target="_blank" href="http://insidedenver.com/drmn/local/article/0,1299,DRMN_15_4233341,00.html" title=""Westerners changing way they see animals"">"Westerners changing way they see animals"</a>) on <a target="_blank" href="http://www.warnercnr.colostate.edu/NRRT/hdnr/human.htm" title="a new study by Colorado State University">a new study by Colorado State University</a> that measured peopleâ€™s attitudes toward wildlife in 19 Western states. The study, led by CSU professor Mike Manfredo, shows that in the Rocky Mountain West, Coloradoans have the cuddliest attitude toward animals, with 34.9% of respondents charting as â€œanimal lovers, ranging from wildlife watchers to animal rights advocates, who donâ€™t condone hunting or fishing,â€? versus 34.1% who believe wildlife exists for â€œpersonal or economic uses, such as hunting or fishing.â€? <br />
<br />
New Mexico residents surveyed showed a similar split, with 31.9% supporting the animals-as-friends view, and 35.2% taking the animals-are-good-eating position.  Utah, Montana, and Wyoming residents surveyed espouse more traditional Western values toward wildlife, with between  44 and 48% falling into the hunting and fishing camp and between 18-20% favoring the furry companion view.  The two outliers in the study were Alaska, in favor of hunters (50% vs. 15.3%) and Hawaii, in favor of animal lovers (40.6% vs. 25.4%). Among the 19 states, only Hawaii and California had a higher percentage of animal lovers than Colorado, which could reflect the fact that many Californians have moved here,  or it could suggest that hunting is simply dying out as an accepted  practice among Colorado residents. <br />
<br />
The CSU study divided respondents between those with the â€œUtilitarian Wildlife Orientation,â€? who regard â€œhunting as a humane and positive activityâ€? and believe that â€œwildlife exists for human use and enjoyment,â€? and those with the â€œMutualism Wildlife Orientationâ€? which â€œis associated with the desire for humans and wildlife to co-exist or live in harmony.â€? Some respondents charted high on both scales (evidencing a â€œpluralisticâ€? attitude toward wildlife), and some charted low on both scales (evidencing a â€œdistancedâ€? attitude toward wildlife).  The study notes that these attitudes toward wildlife have broad implications for public policy decisions.  For example, those who fall into the Utilitarian camp favor the management of â€œwildlife so that humans benefitâ€? and â€œprioritize the needs of humans over wildlife.â€? Those with the Mutualism orientation â€œassign animals rights like humansâ€? and seek to prevent cruelty to animals.<br />
<br />
The exhaustive, 344-page study is available online, and it explores such issues as how and why attitudes toward wildlife are changing, and what people believe should be done about deer overpopulation.  One of the conclusions is that â€œcompared with the other two groups, Utilitarians and Pluralists are older, more likely to hunt, more likely to have lived in the state for a longer period of time, and more likely to be male.â€? If longtime residents are more likely to support hunting and fishing, the increasing influx of newcomers to the region will likely have implications for wildlife policy in the future. <br />

