		<b>Comment By Hal Herring, 11-15-05</b>
		<p>CSU seems to be asking a question that serves to obscure rather than illuminate. Trying to say that there are two separate camps--one that hunts, and one that "loves" wildlife is nuts.<br />
<br />
The most intense and intertwined relationships between mankind and wild animals are a profound mixture of utilitarianism and love. Ask any subsistence hunter, or any number of big game hunters who have been the driving force for wildlife and wildlands conservation and environmental protection in the United States.<br />
The folks who see the wild creatures as "cuddly" <br />
don't seem to pay much attention to, or donate much time or cash, to organizations that protect habitat. And I do not personally know any hunters (I bet they are out there, but I've avoided them) who would ever say something as repulsive as "wildlife exists for the pleasure of human beings." <br />
<br />
If what you've written of the study-and I have not read the study, of course-- is representative, then what it most illuminates is that we desparately need...Ahah, said long ago, by the wonderful <br />
Henry Beston, 1888-1968<br />
The Outermost House<br />
We need another and a wiser and perhaps a more mystical concept of animals ... We patronize them for their incompleteness, for their tragic fate of having taken form so far below ourselves. And therein we err and err greatly. For the animal shall not be measured by man. In a world older and more complete than ours, they move finished and complete, gifted with extensions of the senses we have lost or never attained, living by voices we shall never hear. They are not brethren; they are not underlings; they are other nations, caught with ourselves in the net of life and time, fellow prisoners of the splendor and travail of the earth <br />
End quote<br />
<br />
Try asking Coloradans about that and see what the repsonses would be! <br />
<br />
<br />
Thanks, Hal Herring</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 11-15-05</b>
		<p>Hi Hal,<br />
<br />
I don't think I've done justice to the study in this little post--there's a lot of data in the report, and I suggest you check out the link to it if you're interested.  As I understand it, the study doesn't suggest that hunters don't care for animals--It evaluates respondents along these matrices of whether they believe hunting is acceptable or not, whether they do or would hunt personally, or whether they think hunting is completely wrong.  Hunters are more likely to see wildlife as something that should be managed for human benefit (which doesn't mean they think wildlife should be extinguished or disrespected) and then on the extreme other end, according to the Rocky Mountain News, the study found some people "who said if there was an accident involving a human and an animal, they would help the animal first."  I haven't been able to digest the whole 344 pages of it yet, but I think that the study concludes that most hunters feel a close bond with animals, even though their attitude differs in key ways from non-hunters.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Hal Herring, 11-15-05</b>
		<p>I'll read it, Jenny. Thanks for bringing it to my attention. Sometimes I think that the most basic questions--the ones from which all others spring--is how mankind relates to the rest of creation. We have a dark and repulsive record, shot through in places with a pure light--ie. wilderness protection, the ESA, etc.(laws enacted without concrete motivations of profit or human health concerns)and a huge number of individuals who live lightly and mindfully and can be found in every nation of the world. <br />
I'll leave one last quote if I can find it. <br />
 From Richard Nelson:<br />
I will never know if animals and plants have spirits, if the tree I stand beside is aware of my presence, if respectful gestures bring hunting luck or protect my well-being. But I am absolutely certain it is wise and responsible to behave as if these things were true.</p>
		
